# inkling

A collaborative text editor inspired by Notion. Real-time multiplayer editing with rich text formatting, a nestable page tree, cursor presence, and persistent storage.

Default to using Bun instead of Node.js.

- Use `bun <file>` instead of `node <file>` or `ts-node <file>`
- Use `bun install` instead of `npm install`
- Use `bun run <script>` instead of `npm run <script>`
- Use `bunx <package>` instead of `npx <package>`
- Bun automatically loads .env, so don't use dotenv.

## Project Structure

```
src/
  client/                    React frontend
    index.tsx                React entry point + App + routing
    Layout.tsx               App shell with collapsible/resizable sidebar
    Layout/Sidebar.tsx       Page tree, real-time updates, drag-and-drop
    Page.tsx                 Page feature (title, editor, collaboration)
    Page/Editor.tsx          Tiptap editor with floating toolbar
    common/CableClient.ts    ActionCable-inspired WebSocket client
    common/fetch.ts          Auth-ready fetch wrapper (auto-JSON, ApiError)
  server/                    Bun.serve backend
    index.ts                 Server entry (routes + WebSocket upgrade)
    Cable.ts                 WebSocket hub (subscribe, broadcast, relay)
    Cable/DocumentManager.ts In-memory Yjs docs + DB persistence
    Pages.ts                 REST API route handlers (CRUD + tree ops)
    Pages/Page.ts            Page model (baked-orm, soft delete)
  shared/                    Code shared between client and server
    slugify.ts               URL slug generation
    ancestry.ts              Cycle-safe parent walk for tree validation
db/
  migrations/                baked-orm migrations (raw SQL in TypeScript)
  schema.ts                  Auto-generated from DB (do not edit)
tests/                       Unit tests (mirrors src/ structure)
e2e/                         Playwright E2E tests
scripts/
  move.ts                    Move files with automatic import updates
  db-cleanup.ts              Drop orphaned per-worktree databases
```

## Key Conventions

- **File naming**: PascalCase for components/classes, lowercase for utilities.
- **Feature structure**: `Feature.tsx` sits alongside `Feature/` which holds its internals. No `index.ts` files.
- **Path aliases**: `@client/*`, `@server/*`, `@shared/*`, `@db/*` (defined in tsconfig.json).
- **Moving files**: Use `bun scripts/move.ts <source> <dest>` to move files. It updates all imports automatically.
- **Inline types**: Don't create named `interface`/`type` declarations for single-use props or shapes.

## Database

PostgreSQL 18. ORM is [baked-orm](https://www.npmjs.com/package/baked-orm).

```bash
bun bake db create <name>        # Create database
bun bake db generate <name>      # Generate migration
bun bake db migrate up           # Run pending migrations
bun bake db migrate down         # Rollback last migration
```

Schema is auto-generated at `db/schema.ts` after each migration. Don't edit it manually.

## Server

`Bun.serve()` with routes + WebSocket. Don't use express.

- REST routes defined in `src/server/Pages.ts`.
- WebSocket upgrade at `/ws`, managed by `Cable` class.
- `DELETE` is a hard delete in development and a soft delete (`discarded_at`) in production.

## Real-time Collaboration

- **Single Y.Doc per page** — all blocks live in one Yjs document, stored as `yjs_state bytea` on the `pages` table.
- **Yjs** for CRDT-based editing (synced via `doc:page_{id}` WebSocket channel).
- **Custom Yjs provider** bridges Yjs sync protocol to the CableClient.
- **Undo/redo** uses Yjs UndoManager via Tiptap's Collaboration extension.

## Testing

```bash
bun test              # Bun unit tests (tests/)
bun run test:e2e      # Playwright E2E tests (e2e/)
bun run check         # Biome lint + knip dead code + tsc type check
```

## CI

GitHub Actions runs on push to `main` and on pull requests (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`). Three jobs: `check` (lint + types + dead code), `unit-tests` (against Postgres 18), and `e2e-tests` (Playwright, gated on `dorny/paths-filter`).

## Browser Debugging

Chrome DevTools MCP is available for browser inspection. Use it instead of Playwright for debugging and profiling tasks — it connects to the user's actual browser tab via CDP.

Requires Chrome running with `--remote-debugging-port=9222`. Reserve Playwright for E2E test authoring, not ad-hoc debugging.
